# Components

Write components that are small, mobile-first, and cheap to render. This is an
ISR e-shop — bundle size and Core Web Vitals directly affect SEO and conversion.

## Mobile-First

- Design for ~360px width first; add overrides for larger screens.
- Use MUI breakpoints consistently: `xs < sm < md < lg < xl`.
- Prefer CSS Grid / Flexbox layouts that reflow naturally over JS-driven layouts.
- Avoid rendering two copies of the same content for mobile vs desktop; use
  responsive CSS. If you truly need different trees (rare — see
  `ParagraphContainer` in `ApieMus`), keep them minimal and comment why.

## Performance

- **Images**: always use `next/image`. Provide `width`, `height`, `sizes`, and
  meaningful `alt`. Set `priority` **only** for above-the-fold LCP images.
- **Imports**: use `lodash-es` (tree-shakable), never `lodash`. Use named imports
  from `@mui/material` / `@mui/icons-material`.
- **Memoization**: wrap expensive or frequently-re-rendered components in `memo`
  (see `PageHead`). Don't memo trivial components.
- **Client vs static**: prefer content that renders at build time via ISR. Only
  reach for `useEffect` / client state when truly interactive.
- **3rd-party scripts**: route through Partytown (`type="text/partytown"`).

## Structure

- Keep components under ~150 lines; split when they grow.
- Co-locate the component, its styles (`<name>Styles.ts`), and any `.module.css`
  in the same folder.
- Extract reusable pieces into `src/components/`; page-specific pieces stay in
  `src/pages/<PageName>/`.
- Route files in `pages/` should only handle `getStaticProps` / `getStaticPaths`
  and render the page component — no JSX logic.
